        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Aitchison had been suggested to Cupples by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1494.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Robert Elliot</ref> as a breeder worth contacting for information about the proportions of the sexes (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6775.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Robert Elliot to George Cupples, 4 June 1869</ref>). This letter was enclosed in the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6789.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from George Cupples, 20 June 1869</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD cited Aitchison for this information and for returns on sheep in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 1: 305.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">In the table, the first column (before the point) represents groups of twenty, the second (after the point) units up to nineteen. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6809F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from William Aitchison to George Cupples, 30 June 1869</ref>. Sheep were traditionally counted in a vigesimal counting system. Cupples added conventionally written figures at the side of the table.</note>
        </div>        
            
